issue.title: TUTORIAL: for anyone wondering how to have multiple instance
issue.body:
if you installed with atuomatic mode and wondering how to run multiple psiphon with different configs this is the way :)
```
sudo /etc/psiphon/psiphon-tunnel-core-x86_64 -config fr.config
sudo /etc/psiphon/psiphon-tunnel-core-x86_64 -config de.config
and so on

```

comment.body:
#!/bin/bash

# Exit on error and show commands
set -e
set -x

# Check if running as root
if [ "$EUID" -ne 0 ]; then
    echo "Please run as root using sudo"
    exit 1
fi

# Update system and install prerequisites
apt-get update
apt-get install -y wget jq iptables

# Create necessary directories
mkdir -p /etc/psiphon/instance{0,A,B,C,D,E}
mkdir -p /usr/share/psiphon/
mkdir -p /var/log/psiphon/

# Download necessary files
echo "Starting downloads"
wget -O /usr/share/psiphon/psiphon-tunnel-core-x86_64 \
    https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Psiphon-Labs/psiphon-tunnel-core-binaries/master/linux/psiphon-tunnel-core-x86_64
wget -O /tmp/psiphon.config.base \
    https://raw.githubusercontent.com/SpherionOS/PsiphonLinux/main/psiphon.config
echo "Core files downloaded"

# Function to create config files with guaranteed 0.0.0.0 binding
create_config() {
    local instance=$1
    local http_port=$2
    local socks_port=$3
    
    cp /tmp/psiphon.config.base /etc/psiphon/$instance/psiphon.config
    
    # Use jq for reliable JSON manipulation
    jq --argjson http_port "$http_port" \
       --argjson socks_port "$socks_port" \
       '.LocalHttpProxyPort = $http_port | 
        .LocalSocksProxyPort = $socks_port | 
        .BindInterface = "0.0.0.0" | 
        .AllowNoAuthorization = true' \
        /etc/psiphon/$instance/psiphon.config > /tmp/temp_config.json
        
    mv /tmp/temp_config.json /etc/psiphon/$instance/psiphon.config
}

# Create configs for all instances
create_config "instance0" 8080 1080
create_config "instanceA" 3169 4169
create_config "instanceB" 5169 6169
create_config "instanceC" 7169 8169
create_config "instanceD" 9169 10169
create_config "instanceE" 11169 12169

# Create launcher scripts
for instance in instance0 instanceA instanceB instanceC instanceD instanceE; do
    # For instance0, the command is just 'psiphon'
    if [ "$instance" = "instance0" ]; then
        command_name="psiphon"
    else
        # Remove the word 'instance' to get A, B, etc.
        suffix="${instance#instance}"
        command_name="psiphon$suffix"
    fi
    
    cat > /usr/bin/$command_name <<EOF
#!/bin/bash
cd /etc/psiphon/$instance
exec /usr/share/psiphon/psiphon-tunnel-core-x86_64 -config psiphon.config
EOF
    chmod +x /usr/bin/$command_name
done

# Make core binary executable
chmod +x /usr/share/psiphon/psiphon-tunnel-core-x86_64

# Configure firewall
ports=(8080 1080 3169 4169 5169 6169 7169 8169 9169 10169 11169 12169)
for port in "${ports[@]}"; do
    iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport $port -j ACCEPT
    echo "Allowed ALL to port $port"
done

# Save firewall rules
mkdir -p /etc/iptables
iptables-save > /etc/iptables/rules.v4

# Create supervisor script
cat > /usr/local/bin/psiphon-supervisor <<'EOF'
#!/bin/bash
trap 'kill $(jobs -p); exit 0' SIGTERM SIGINT

for instance in instance0 instanceA instanceB instanceC instanceD instanceE; do
    cd "/etc/psiphon/$instance"
    /usr/share/psiphon/psiphon-tunnel-core-x86_64 -config psiphon.config &
done

# Wait indefinitely
while true; do
    sleep 3600 &
    wait $!
done
EOF
chmod +x /usr/local/bin/psiphon-supervisor

# Create systemd service
cat > /etc/systemd/system/psiphon-multi.service <<'EOF'
[Unit]
Description=Psiphon Multi-Instance VPN Service
After=network.target

[Service]
Type=simple
ExecStart=/usr/local/bin/psiphon-supervisor
Restart=always
RestartSec=5s
StandardOutput=syslog
StandardError=syslog
SyslogIdentifier=psiphon-multi

[Install]
WantedBy=multi-user.target
EOF

# Create uninstaller
cat > pluninstaller_multi <<'EOF'
#!/bin/bash
# Stop and disable service
systemctl stop psiphon-multi
systemctl disable psiphon-multi

# Remove files
rm -rf /etc/psiphon
rm -f /usr/bin/psiphon
rm -f /usr/bin/psiphon{A,B,C,D,E}
rm -rf /usr/share/psiphon
rm -f /usr/local/bin/psiphon-supervisor
rm -f /etc/systemd/system/psiphon-multi.service

# Reset firewall rules
ports=(8080 1080 3169 4169 5169 6169 7169 8169 9169 10169 11169 12169)
for port in "${ports[@]}"; do
    iptables -D INPUT -p tcp --dport $port -j ACCEPT 2>/dev/null
done

# Save firewall rules
iptables-save > /etc/iptables/rules.v4

echo "Psiphon multi-instance uninstalled"
EOF
chmod +x pluninstaller_multi

# Enable and start service
systemctl daemon-reload
systemctl enable --now psiphon-multi

# Final verification
echo "Waiting for instances to start (30 seconds)..."
sleep 30

echo ""
echo "Verifying port bindings:"
echo "=============================================================="
for port in "${ports[@]}"; do
    if ss -tulpn | grep ":$port" | grep -q "0.0.0.0"; then
        echo "Port $port: SUCCESS (listening on 0.0.0.0)"
    else
        echo "Port $port: FAILED (not listening correctly)"
    fi
done
echo "=============================================================="

echo ""
echo "Installation completed! All instances should be accessible from your LAN."
echo "Use 'systemctl status psiphon-multi' to check service status"
echo "Uninstall with: sudo ./pluninstaller_multi"

Issue #261: adding missing dense descriptor and delete unnecessary seâ€¦ (#288)

Prior to this MR, the PageRank implementation does not pass the dense descriptor when it could, while it includes the use of the expensive `invert_mask` in its performance-critical loop. Mask inversion is expensive since it requires iterating over the full vector range, while, in this case, the inverted mask is constant. Additionally, an unnecessary call to `grb::set` preceded a call to the out-of-place `grb::eWiseApply`. Hence, this MR introduces the following changes:
- the inverted mask is precomputed once, while in the performance-critical loop the precomputed inversion is reused as a structural mask;
- the PR algorithm is reviewed to pass the dense descriptor whenever possible;
- the PR algorithm no longer makes the detected unnecessary call to `grb::set`.

This improvement does come at the cost of one additional work-space vector that is now required for the PageRank implementation.

In implementing these fixes, the following feature has been added:
- the `grb::eWiseLambda` now takes a descriptor template argument. This was previously accepted in the nonblocking backend, but was missing from the specification as well as missing in the implementations of other backends.

The following bugs were encountered and fixed with this MR:
- mixed-domain vector-to-scalar reductions were bugged for the nonblocking backend: when the second (underlying) monoid domain type did not match its third (output) domain type, a compiler error would be returned. This MR fixes the behaviour for both left- and right-handed reductions;
- the descriptors for multiple-vector eWiseLambdas were not correctly propagated for the nonblocking backend.

Thanks to Aristeidis and Benjamin for detecting and fixing a variety of issues this MR addresses!

633 Provide grb::foldl/foldr( [in,out] T&, [in] Matrix<D>, monoid ) (#188)

This MR specifies and implements matrix-to-scalar reduction routines. The matrix may be input masked (by a separate, second given matrix). The reductions take either a commutative monoid or a semiring -- if the latter, its additive monoid will be used for reduction (which, by definition of a semiring, is also commutative). The monoid variants cannot handle pattern matrices, and cannot handle the `add_identity` descriptor-- for these, the "one" identity of a semiring is necessary.
Since with ALP/GraphBLAS, operators, from which monoids and semirings are comprised, may have different input and different output domains (i.e., `A x B -> C`), this MR introduces left-looking and right-looking variants of this reduction operation and calls them `foldl` and `foldr`, respectively. This is in line with the previously already included primitives for scalar-to-scalar and vector-to-scalar reduction.

The MR introduces exhaustive unit testing for the new functionality, and, as always, includes code style fixes in files related and unrelated to this new feature. Notable other inclusions:
- an internal utility has been introduced that helps asserting return codes are synchronised across multiple user processes;
- a systematic way to derive index-translation lambdas for so-called "union coordinates" has been introduced. These lambdas are by convention used as a mechanism to let the BSP1D backend (or any distributed backend) translate process-local calls to any single-process final backend. This new feature may yet be further improved-- see GitHub issue #322 .

Many thanks to Benjamin for the implementation and testing for this one!

665 set up continuous benchmarking (#300)

Provides a site-specific setup for continuous benchmarking. This will run on our internal cluster; thus, should a third party want to set up continuous benchmarking, the changes introduced here should be adapted to the specifics of the third-party site.

Fix missing header in utils.hpp (#324)

Recent commits reordered includes, which resulted in GCC correctly detecting `utils.hpp` when compiling in debug mode (i.e., compiling with `_DEBUG`) that `iostream` should have been included but was not. This MR adds the required include.

a selection operator (#271)

This MR introduces the matrix selection feature -- given a operator that takes matrix nonzero coordinates and a value as arguments and produces a boolean, elements from an input matrix are selected to be copied in some output matrix. This primitive operates in an out-of-place fashion. In-place semantics may be achieved via a temporary (pattern) matrix and fold, and thus are currently not planned to be added. Standard matrix selection operators such as (strictly) lower triangular etc. are provided, including type traits for them. Non-standard selection operators provided by users may be employed also since the new grb::select primitive accepts arbitrary lambda functions as a selection operator as well.

This MR also fixes a bug for the BSP1D and hybrid eWiseApply on matrices with the resize mode, which returned `SUCCESS` even if one or more processes encountered an issue (such as out-of-memory conditions). The MR includes unit tests for matrix distributions and the new select operator, as well as code style fixes in related and unrelated files.

Fix a performance bug in the nonblocking backend (#326)

Since #292 , a performance bug has snuck in for the nonblocking backend that causes it to underperform for small-to-mid sizes matrices (up to size 1.5 million). This bug was not present in v0.7. It had been present in the `develop` branch from MR #292 up to this MR (#326).

For larger matrices, the bug stifled performance of the nonblocking backend, causing it to be on par with or exceed the`reference_omp` backend, but not by as much as it should have.

This MR fixes the bug, which was found to be the following: since a tile consists of many elements, the introduced static schedule should use a blocksize of one, and not the default larger blocksize. Taking a larger blocksize in fact simulates (in a suboptimal way) the use of nonblocking execution with a cache size that is multiplied with the blocksize. With this MR, the blocksize is explicitly set to one instead.

249 alp passes 0 as max calls to lpf collectives initialisation (#302)

This MR fixes a bug where `lpf_coll_t` was not initialised properly. This bug never resulted in a noticeable issue, since the present implementation of the LPF collectives ignores the erroneous argument that ALP was passing in. The nevertheless not-up-to-spec initialisation of LPF collectives happened repeatedly throughout the code base. This MR totally overhauls the implementation of the collectives to address the issue.

Within LPF, there are two classes of collectives: the one exposed via the public API `grb::collectives<>`, and raw internal collectives that are used in the implementation of e.g. the `BSP1D` and `hybrid` backends. Prior to this MR, the implementations of these collectives were disjoint, while with this MR, both types of collectives are managed by a shared context (internally encapsulated by the `BSP1D_Data` object). This central management means every process maintains but a single `lpf_coll_t` instance that is reused every time a public or internal collective is called.

The revision of the collectives also now includes a systematic choice where collectives on scalars are orchestrated through the global buffer so as to prevent having to register the scalar memory addresses every time a collective is called. This is likely to cut latency costs significantly compared to the status prior to this MR. For collectives on arrays, the source and/or destination arrays will be registered which incurs a latency costs-- but a cost that, assuming large enough array sizes, is much lower than that of having to copy the payload to and from the global buffer. 

Features this MR introduces in realising the refactored collectives:
- a notion of a final backend, which is the final backend a composed backend relies on. The FinalBackend class collects a set of minimal and low-level functions that all final backends should provide, such as memcpy; and
- a utility that translates LPF error codes into corresponding ALP error codes.

Other issues this MR addresses:
- BSP1D did not seem to handle some border cases of `grb::setElement` correctly -- these would trigger only in out-of-memory conditions, or in erroneous use of the primitive, so impact of the bug is expected to be minor;
- the `grb::setElement` and `grb::select` base specifications did not list all error conditions or did not do so correctly, herewith fixed;
- a metabug in `grb::select` had in `_DEBUG` mode an attempt to print an iterator to `stdout`, instead of first dereferencing it-- herewith fixed.

As always, the MR includes both related and unrelated code style fixes.

279 bug in move assignment of matrices (#286)

Aleksa uncovered a bug where move-assigning matrices could result in container IDs not explicitly being removed. Since IDs are created on the basis of unique keys and the unique keys are derived from pointers, the following could (and did) happen: on creating a new matrix, a new ID is requested based on the same pointer the retained ID was also created with. This was detected by the internal mechanism keeping track of IDs, and resulted in an exception.

This MR fixes the bug by removing the ID once the container with the original pointer is destroyed via a move. Even if a subsequent allocation then happens to return the same pointer, the internal state is now clean and a new ID is successfully derived. The MR also strengthens the `getID` unit test to have been able to detect this issue.

The MR also includes a hotfix for an issue detected by our internal CI: on defining full debug tracing (`-D_DEBUG`), various new `BSP1D` code introduced with the previous commit did not compile-- herewith, that is fixed as well.

Finally, this MR -- now again fully related with the issue at hand -- improves `_DEBUG` tracing in `bsp1d/matrix.hpp`, and fixes a similar issue for the `BSP1D` backend: there, prior to this MR, move-assignment would result in never-deleted IDs and a small memory leak. Because of the memory leak, the bug never materialised in the same way it did for the `reference` backend, though nevertheless with this MR now correctly removes the ID as part of a move-assign and prevents the memory leak.

Thanks to Aleksa Milisavljevic @aleksamilisavljevic for detecting and fixing this bug for the `reference` backend!

333 current parallel spgemm cannot be merged (#334)

Concept release notes:

This MR provides a novel implementation for the sparse matrix--sparse matrix multiplication, `grb::mxm`. It modifies the specifications in the following ways:

 1. the `mxm` is now in-place, meaning, it computes C += AB. This was intended a long time ago, but somehow the `mxm` was never adapted until now. If the old behaviour is desired, first clear C (`grb::clear`) before calling `mxm`.

 2. the `grb::resize` now retains old nonzeroes, and (therefore) calls to resize must request a capacity that is larger (or equal) to the current number of values in the container, or otherwise `grb::ILLEGAL` shall be returned.

The newly implemented mxm uses as many threads as internal buffers allow. It still follows Gustavson's approach, where now every thread employs its own private sparse accumulator (SPA)-- which is why the size of the global buffer determines the parallelism of the approach. At least one SPA is guaranteed as the first thread will use the output matrix buffers for its SPA-- threads beyond that first one will use any remaining space in the global buffer. Note that the global buffer size is Theta(m+n+nz) for any matrix in the ALP context, while the SPA memory requirements are proportional to n (or m, if transposed)-- therefore, if nz ~ cn, then this new implementation allows the `mxm` to proceed with Theta(c) threads.

Regarding the `resize`, recall that the old behaviour was to clear the given container. The rationale for change this behaviour is that it became apparent these semantics make it both awkward to use as well as implement the `RESIZE` phase of the `mxm`.

This awkwardness was never observed for level-{1,2} primitives because all current implementations use a fixed full capacity for vector data.

Some related specification clarifications were added to that of the `resize`: whether backends allow for shrinking memory usage after a call to `resize` is defined by its performance semantics. The functional semantics leave this behaviour as optional (and current implementations do not ever shrink capacities).

This MR also includes the following bugfixes:
 - [functional bug] the `RESIZE` phase for the masked `grb::set` for matrices sometimes did not resize to a large-enough capacity
 - [functional bug] in the binsearch utility. Expected impact is nil as the function presently is not used from within ALP
 - [performance bug] the dense descriptor in `grb::set(vector,vector,vector)` could erroneously be ignored
 - [performance bug] the analytic model in the `grb::set` for matrices could erroneously select way too many threads, lowering performance significantly
 - [performance bug] same as the directly preceding item, but for the OpenMP prefix sum utility
 - [performance bug] same as the preceding items, but for `grb::select`
 - [performance bug] the fold-matrix-to-scalar unit test used copy-by-value instead of const-reference capture. This has no effect on user code.

This MR also includes the following new features:
 - [utils] a utility that determines the maximum argument for which a monotonic decreasing function on a given range returns its maximum is provided
 - [utils] an OpenMP prefix-sum variant that also shifts all entries one position to the right has been provided
 - [utils] an unordered-memmove has been implemented, with both sequential and OpenMP parallel variants (used by the new in-place `mxm`)
 - [debugging] more targeted debug flags (e.g., `_DEBUG_UTILS_PREFIXSUM` to debug only that particular utility or `_DEBUG_REFERENCE_BLAS3` to debug only level-3 primitives in the reference backends. Defining `_DEBUG` will still enable all debug outputs)
 - [native] a non_owning_view descriptor has been introduced as a requirement for an ALP native interface. This descriptor indicates that containers are used whose associated memory is not managed by ALP.
 - [internal] The coordinates class now supports calling a parallel set or a sequential one (for use as thread-local SPAs)

Tests have been modified as follows:
 - [unit] the SpMSpM multiplication unit test now also tests in-place behaviour
 - [unit] the SpMSpM multiplication unit test now also tests the force_row_major descriptor, which now appears as a separate test in the test suite
 - [unit] the capacity unit test has been brought in-line with the updated specifications of `grb::resize`
 - [unit] the id test now uses 100 tries instead of a 1000 for CI performance reasons
 - [unit] the parallelRegularIterators test implicitly and unintendedly cast a double to int
 - [performance] the SpMSpM multiplication driver can now benchmark CRS only also

As always, this MR also includes some code style fixes and provides some missing code documentations.

342 execution issue with custom preconditioning function in conjugate gradient non blocking backend (#344)

This PCG algorithm allows for user-defined preconditioners to be supplied by the user. This functionality, in turn, was then used by the solver and KML_Solver transition paths to offer ready-made libraries for which users could supply their own preconditioners via function pointers. Those preconditioners would operate on standard raw C arrays, thus making use of the ALP native interface -- however, the PCG algorithm in ALP/GraphBLAS implicitly assumed the preconditioner action was implemented as an ALP function; i.e., not using the native interface.

This mismatch causes issues in combination with the nonblocking backend, which guarantees valid nonblocking execution for pure ALP programs, but in combination with native code requires calls to `grb::wait`.

This MR introduces a template argument to indicate whether the preconditioner may make use of native calls. This is done by extending the already-existing Boolean argument that previously indicated whether to apply preconditioning-- this is now become an `int` rather than `bool`, with `0` indicating no preconditioning, `1` indicating non-native (ALP-based) user-defined preconditioning, and `2` indicating possibly-native user-defined preconditioning. Only in the latter case does this MR furthermore activate the new calls to `grb::wait` that are necessary for native preconditioning functions.

An alternative design has that the authors of user-defined preconditioners should call `grb::wait` before taking and operating on native views of ALP/GraphBLAS vectors. In this design, the reported issue #342 would in fact indicate a bug in the related transition libraries. Comparing the implemented solution with this alternative design has that more care should be taken by those supplying user-defined preconditioners, and we instead prefer to make the life of any ALP user easier; hence the present solution was taken instead.

The bug that this MR fixes affected the PCG transition paths only; i.e., users of `solver.h` and/or `kml_iss.h`, only when using custom preconditioners, and only non-diagonal preconditioner actions.

347 only build bench_kernels and bench_kernels_omp for targets that depend on it (fix coverage tests in internal CI)

After merge #355 the internal CI coverage jobs on the main `develop` branch fail due to errors related to the `bench_kernels` and `bench_kernels_omp` library targets. This is odd since those two libraries are only required by three specific performance tests - fma, dot, and reduce - while the coverage jobs rely only on unit tests: thus #355 appears to somehow have laid bare an older issue with the CMake infra, which are fixed in this MR.

Additionally, this MR renames the sequential `fma`, `dot`, and `reduce` performance test binaries to the more-descriptive `fma-sequential`, `dot-sequential`, and `reduce-sequential`, respectively.

363 missing grb wait for collecting execution times (#364)

This MR adds calls to `grb::wait` for performance and other tests where its omission may result in false performance results for backends that perform nonblocking execution. This MR also fixes the following meta-bugs:
- the return code of the label propagation algorithm was ignored in the performance benchmark driver,
- same for the label propagation smoke test,
- some initialisation operations were not error-checked in the BiCGstab smoke test,
- same for the CG smoke tests,
- re-enabled `sleep(1)` in the HPCG benchmark to detect system variabilities.

All above changes only affect the ALP test suite. The MR does include one change that cannot be classified as a meta-bug:
- the Pregel API constructor did not account for nonblocking behaviour, and should wait before returning to adhere to RAII.

This changes the behaviour of all user applications based on ALP/Pregel in combination with the nonblocking backend; and only its performance characteristics (in particular, some of the initialisation of ALP/Pregel on some particular graph was previously be postponed until the execution of the first Pregel program-- after this change, all initialisation will have guaranteed to complete by the end of the constructor call). ALP/Pregel programs based on other backends remain unchanged in behaviour.

This MR also improves, on occasion, error reporting within the test suite, and, as always, includes code style fixes. Thank you to @aristeidis-mastoras for flagging these issues and providing the initial fixes!

Add early exit in preconditioned CG when initial residual is below tolerance (#350)

Previously, the (preconditioned) Conjugate Gradient (CG) algorithm applies the preconditioner before checking whether the current residual already met the required tolerance. The changes from this MR allows the CG to return immediately when the initial residual is small enough, avoiding the unnecessary cost of a preconditioner call. This change can improve performance in cases where the initial guess is already close to the solution. Thanks to @ChristosMatzoros for proposing this enhancement!

360 transition path allocates workspace vector data for sparse information (#361)

Previous to this MR the solver transition path allocates workspace vector data using the standard ALP vector constructors, which results allocating a sparse accumulator (SPA). SPAs are used for ALP/GraphBLAS vectors to handle sparsity efficiently. However, in the use case of exactly this solver transition path, the workspace vector data is guaranteed dense, which results in unused memory. This clashes with a use case where as many independent solves as possible are to be handled simultaneously, which actually results in a memory-constrained scenario. To effectively support this use case, this MR uses the transition path vector wrappers to, instead of using the standard ALP/GraphBLAS vector constructors, wrap around a given memory region instead. This memory region is of size n times `sizeof(T)`, where n is the vector size and `T` is the vector element type, thus allocating precisely what is required for a dense vector and not more.

Additionally, the solver transition path API now can take hints when creating a PCG solver handle that control how much and how the memory should be allocated: with or without NUMA support (in the aforementioned memory constrained many-solver scenario, a local allocation policy may be preferred), and with or without preconditioner support (preconditioned solves require one extra workspace vector to be allocated). These are hints: the specification of the transition path allows implementations to ignore hints. The present ALP implementation introduced with this MR only ignores a requested NUMA-aware allocation if it was configured without `libnuma` support-- in all other cases the hints are respected. The "hint-semantic" also allows this MR's implementation to still execute a preconditioned solve successfully, even if a hint was given that this would not happen. In this situation, on-demand allocation using ALP/GraphBLAS' standard vector allocation mechanism will still be used, in which case unused memory will still be allocated. Additionally, in this case, a warning is printed to stderr.

While options are now possible, the standard constructors available prior to this MR are still present. These will default to NUMA-aware allocations with preconditioning, which is the case closest to the constructor as it was and also reflective of the most common use case.

Finally, this MR allows for users to supply their own workspace as a pointer-size pair. This supports perhaps even more exotic use cases where the user program has their own non-standard allocation schemes -- or, if applications would want to reuse buffers between different phases of their application, again when in a memory-constrained setting.

Thanks to @ChristosMatzoros for integration with this particular use case, testing the fixes, as well as the final code review!

Fixes static-assert failure from unused code path #371 (#372)

@djelovina observed it was possible for a static assertion from the sparse code path of `grb::eWiseApply` to trigger while passing in the `dense` descriptor to that primitive. This MR ensures that the corresponding sparse code path's static assert now does *not* trigger when the `dense` descriptor is given, using the "C++11 way" of ensuring so. Issue #373 has been raised to handle it more elegantly using the C++17 `if constexpr`.

Additionally, in handling this MR it was found that a similar static-assert was missing from the dense code path for `grb::eWiseApply`, and has been added. The MR also enhances the warnings to the `right_assign_if` and `left_assign_if` operators regarding their use in out-of-place primitives which is what led to detecting this bug.

Thanks to Denis for finding and reporting the issue, as well as for help reviewing this fix.

Your `iam-automation.yaml` file contains the path from the root of your Git repository to your CloudFormation template as well as the parameters and tags for your stack. When changes are committed to your repository, CloudFormation automatically updates the stack, its parameters, and tags.

Edit your `iam-automation.yaml` file and commit the changes to your repository. Make sure that you commit the changes to the path and branch in the repository that are specified in the deployment file.

issue.title: Enable replacement of a shop by a parcel locker or vending machine
issue.body:
**Use case**
I noticed several cases where a space formerly occupied by a small shop was used to house one or more parcel lockers or vending machines. This is a growing trend here in Sofia, but I've also seen such converted shop spaces on holiday in Italy. However, in SC, shops can only be replaced by other "places" while vending machines and parcel lockers can only be added through the "things" overlay. The workaround I use now is to add the machines in the "things" overlay and leave a note that the shop node can be deleted. Back home I often cut-paste the machine tags to the former shop node to preserve its history, and delete the machine node that I created in SC [example](https://www.openstreetmap.org/changeset/170428903).


**Proposed Solution**
1. Redefine parcel lockers and vending machines as "services" that belong in the "places" list (i.e. move them from "things" to "places", as suggested here https://github.com/streetcomplete/StreetComplete/issues/5152#issuecomment-1706595942
2. Make parcel lockers and vending machines available as "shops" in addition to being available as "places".

comment.body:
**TL;DR:** issue happens rare enough that leaving a note is probably just fine, and:

- possible solutions seem hacky/confusing or their prerequisites not likely to happen soon ( e.g. `shop=vending_machine` landing in id-tagging-schema)
- it would be wrong re-tagging if that ex-`shop=*` was on an area (e.g. `building=retail`) and not on single node

---

> However, since this tag is not supported by id-tagging-schema, (and unlikely to be added due to how rare it is) you currently cannot add it via SC.

Yes, the threshold for inclusion in id-tagging-schema seems to [about 1000 uses](https://github.com/openstreetmap/id-tagging-schema/pull/1302#issuecomment-2254972778), so `shop=vending_machine` needs about a 10-fold increase to be eligible; and current [growth graph](https://taghistory.raifer.tech/?#***/shop/vending_machine) does not make that likely (unless it happens to grow exponentially, e.g. if someone invest time to promote / map them).

> 1. Redefine parcel lockers and vending machines as "services" that belong in the "places" list (i.e. move them from "things" to "places"

Uh, I don't like that. So parking machines, ATMs, luggage lockers, photo booths, sanitary dump stations, public telephones, binoculars and many other ["Things"](https://github.com/streetcomplete/StreetComplete/blob/master/app/src/commonMain/kotlin/de/westnordost/streetcomplete/osm/Things.kt#L38) that are likely to have `fee=yes`  (IOW, are "services") should/would become "Places" too? 

_And_ there are many others which don't have fee, but would properly fit under services, e.g. survellience cameras, water taps, bbqs, hunting stands, garbage dumpsters, device charging stations etc.
At that point IMHO, we might we well get rid of distinction and group both Things and Places under single "POI" group.
(but that is obviously unwanted, as it makes adding POIs too crowded)

> 2. Make parcel lockers and vending machines available as "shops" in addition to being available as "places".

Somewhat better, but I'm still not a big fan of that either as it feels hacky and introduces confusion (some things are shown in both Things and replacement shops, but others aren't)...

---

Since it **does not seem to happen all that often**:

> I noticed several cases

probably leaving a Note is OK  "solution"[^1] (and I'd guess preferred to other solutions, such as ugly hacks injecting extra values like `shop=vending_machine` in id-tagging-schema so they could be used as replacement shop).

Especially because one can never fully fix it, as there are many other things that could have replaced that shop there, but which are not present in [SC "Places"](https://github.com/streetcomplete/StreetComplete/blob/master/app/src/commonMain/kotlin/de/westnordost/streetcomplete/osm/Places.kt#L34) (or even in id-tagging-schema at all).


Also, **importantly** note that if the ex-`shop=*` was tagged on an area (e.g. `building=retail`), it would be simply incorrect to re-tag that whole area to `amenity=parcel_locker` (as parcel locker itself does not take *all* that area - you wouldn't be able to enter the building otherwise!) or [amenity=vending_machine](https://wiki.openstreetmap.org/wiki/Tag:amenity%3Dvending_machine) (which is not even specified _can_ be used on an area), so retagging to those values would have to be limited to just nodes, not areas, which introduces much more complexity for a little gain.

[^1]: or of course, if one uses SCEE, they can just use raw tags functionality to change it immediately on the ground

> @copilot In multi-file mode, using `new Audio()` and `new Image()` in the JavaScript code to load data from a panel audio or image file doesnâ€™t seem to work. Please fix this. Hereâ€™s a simple examp...

Fixed! The issue where `new Audio()` and `new Image()` couldn't load data from virtual panel files in multi-file mode has been resolved.

**Solution implemented:**
- Added Audio constructor override to intercept `new Audio(src)` calls and check virtual file system
- Added Image constructor override to intercept `new Image()` and src property setting
- Both use the same context-aware path resolution as the existing fetch override
- Creates blob URLs for virtual files and falls back to original behavior for external files

**How it works now:**
```javascript
// These now work with virtual files in multi-file mode:
const audio = new Audio('audio/song.mp3');  // Loads from virtual file system
const img = new Image();
img.src = 'images/photo.jpg';               // Also loads from virtual files
```

The constructors seamlessly handle both virtual panel files and external URLs, enabling realistic multi-file development workflows with media assets.

pull_request.body:
## Overview

This PR adds comprehensive arc42 documentation for the external protocol validation tool decision and implementation strategy.

## Changes Made

### ADR-010: External Protocol Validation Tool
- Documents architectural decision to create sophisticated Python TCP client test tool
- Explains context: hex-based protocol validation and performance testing requirements
- Details tool characteristics: external black-box testing, statistical analysis, CI integration
- Positions tool as external validation infrastructure (not architectural component)

### Chapter 8: Testing and Validation Strategy
- Added comprehensive testing and validation strategy section
- Documents protocol format specifications: `#` + 4 hex digits + payload + `!\r\n`
- Defines test scenario categories: compliance, performance, reliability testing
- Describes statistical analysis framework and development workflow integration

### Chapter 11: Enhanced Risk Management
- **Updated R-008** (Industrial Performance Requirements): Added external validation as mitigation
- **Added R-009** (Protocol Implementation Compliance): New technical risk with systematic validation approach
- Enhanced risk mitigation plans to include external validation deployment
- Updated monitoring processes to track validation results and performance baselines

## Technical Context

The external validation tool addresses critical system validation needs:

- **Protocol Compliance**: Systematic validation of hex message format adherence
- **Performance Benchmarking**: 500kBaud throughput and <5ms latency measurement
- **Stress Testing**: System behavior under load, concurrent connections, error scenarios
- **Regression Detection**: Automated validation for continuous integration

## Implementation Scope

Tool characteristics defined in documentation:
- Python TCP client connecting to UART2ETH ports 4001-4004
- Comprehensive test scenarios: valid/invalid messages, performance stress testing
- Statistical analysis: throughput (kbytes/s), latency percentiles (min/median/max RTT)
- Integration with existing logging infrastructure via `persistent_uart_logger.sh`

## Risk Mitigation

This documentation directly addresses:
- **R-008**: Performance requirements validation through external measurement
- **R-009**: Protocol implementation compliance through systematic format testing
- Establishes foundation for comprehensive external validation capability

## Next Steps

Following TDD approach:
1. Implement Python test tool with comprehensive test scenarios
2. Integrate with CI/build validation process  
3. Establish performance baselines and regression detection
